AGI - "A growing number of governments and political authorities are not fulfilling its role as > > the best possible environment for journalism and public law to reliable, independent and diversified news and information". It is the alarm launched by Reporter Senza Frontiere > that in its annual report on freedom of press > in the world emphasizes "an alarming decline in support and respect for media autonomy and an increase in pressure by the state or other political actors".
&nbsp;
Among the countries in which the situation worsened the association signals Argentina of the newly elected President Javier Milei>, while Norway remains in the first place > of the classification - followed by Denmark and Sweden > - with Eritrea finally dropped to the place of North Korea. Afghanistan and Syria, with the latter among the last 10 countries along with China, Iran and North Korea, are among the most significant. But for Rsf the situation has generally worsened in a large number of states: In 138 countries respondents reported that political actors are often involved in disinformation and propaganda, and this is systematic in 31 countries.
&nbsp;
Italy loses five positions in the classification >, from 41st to 46th place, with a quote for the possible sale of the AGI> press agency to the Angelucci group. In 2023 Italy had recovered 17 positions compared to 2022, when it was ranked in 58th place. In the report we make a general mention of the attempt in many countries of political groups to " orchestrate the acquisition of media ecosystems, both of state-owned media that are finished under their control, and of acquisition of private media by allied entrepreneurs". And it is underlined that in Italy "a majority MP is trying to acquire the second press agency, the AGI".&nbsp;
&nbsp;
For the organization that controls the 'health' of press freedom in the world there was "a spectacular imitation of Russian repressive methods" throughout Eastern Europe and Central Asia, which extends to Serbia, "where the pro-government media bring Russian propaganda and authorities threaten Russian journalists in exile." The most difficult region remains the Middle East and North Africa, where the situation is "very serious" in almost half of the countries, with Qatar at the time being the only one where the situation has not been classified either as "difficult" or "very serious".
&nbsp;
Europe was the only region to include countries classified as "good". Here the worst is Greece (88th), behind Hungary and Poland: Athens dismissed the inability to manage the scandal related to the interception of journalists by the secret services and the murder of the black news veteran Giorgos Karaivaz in 2021.&nbsp;
